        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> Why do we keep looking for modifiers when we've already extracted a proper type from the annotation?\n\nHe I understand the code that we need to understand whether type definition contains type modifier. The analysis is done when annotation type is subscript (`T[...]`) - `annotation.is_subscript` condition:\n\nhttps://github.com/cython/cython/blob/62a4106657b31485aed27ecdc42c68012b02cd8c/Cython/Compiler/ExprNodes.py#L15460\n\n This is not ideal because subscript is not used only for type modifier but also type definition (`cython.const` etc.). In order to avoid calling `annotation.analyse_pytyping_modifiers()` we need to craft better condition (based on exact list of type modifiers?). Do you have any idea how to do it?\n\n> [!NOTE] \n> BTW. I consider my attempt to fix this issue in #7490 is correct improvement using similar philosophy, because I am similarly avoiding further analysis when it is clear that the type is not part of `CythonScope`. Do you agree with me?",
